3.1 Welcome to ggplot2

Welcome to ggplot2

  • ggplot2 is an R package for producing statistical, or data, graphics, but it is unlike most other graphics packages because it has a deep underlying grammar.

  • Practically, ggplot2 provides beautiful, hassle-free plots, that take care of fiddly details like drawing legends

  • ggplot2 is designed to work in a layered fashion, starting with a layer showing the raw data then adding layers of annotations and statistical summaries.

3.2 Introduction

Introduction

  • In this lecture, you will learn to make a wide variety of plots with your first ggplot2 function, qplot().

  • qplot, short for quick plot, make it easy to produce complex plots.

3.4 Basic use

Basic use

  • The first two arguments to qplot() are x and y, giving the x- and y-coordinates for the objects on the plot.

  • There is also an optional data argument to specify the data frame that qplot() will look inside before looking for objects in your workspace.

  • Using the data argument is recommended.

Basic use

qplot(carat, price, data = diamonds)

  • The relationship looks exponential, though, so the first thing wed like to do is to transform the variables.

Basic use

qplot(log(carat), log(price), data = diamonds)

  • The relationship now looks linear.

Basic use

  • Arguments can also be combinations of existing variables, so, if we are curious about the relationship between the volume of the diamond (approximated by \(x\times y\times z\)) and its weight, we could do:
qplot(carat, x * y * z, data = diamonds)
  • We would expect the density of diamonds to be constant.

Basic use

qplot(carat, x * y * z, data = diamonds)

3.5 Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

  • qplot can convert a categorical variable in your data into color for you automatically, and it will automatically provide a legend that maps the displayed attributes to the data values.

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

qplot(carat, price, data = dsmall, colour = color)

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

qplot(carat, price, data = dsmall, shape = cut)

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

  • Color, size and shape are all examples of aesthetic attributes.

  • For every aesthetic attribute, there is a function, called a scale, which maps data values to valid values for that aesthetic.

  • It is this scale that controls the appearance of the points and associated legend.

  • You can also manually set the aesthetics using I(), e.g., colour=I("red") or size=I(2). This is not the same as mapping.

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

  • For large datasets, semi-transparent points are often useful to alleviate some of the overplotting.

  • To make a semi-transparent colour you can use the alpha aesthetic, which takes a value between 0 (completely transparent) and 1 (complete opaque).

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

qplot(carat, price, data = diamonds, alpha = I(1/10))

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

qplot(carat, price, data = diamonds, alpha = I(1/100))

Colour, size, shape and other aesthetic attributes

qplot(carat, price, data = diamonds, alpha = I(1/200))

3.6 Plot geoms

Plot geoms

  • qplot is not limited to scatterplot, but can produce almost any kind of plot by varying the geom.

    • geom="point" draws points to produce a scatterplot. This is the default when you supply both x and y arguments to qplot().
    • geom="smooth" fits a smoother to the data and displays the smooth and its standard error.
    • geom="boxplot" produces a box-and-whisker plot to summarize the distribution of a set of points.

Plot geoms

  • For 1d distributions, your choice of geoms is guided by the variable type:

    • For continuous variable,

      • geom="histogram" draws a histogram. This is the default when you only supply an x value to qplot()
      • geom="freqpoly" draws a frequency polygon
      • geom="density" creates a density plot

    • For discrete variable, geom="bar" makes a bar chart.

Adding a smoother to a plot

qplot(carat, price, data = dsmall, geom = c("point", "smooth"))

Adding a smoother to a plot

qplot(carat, price, data = diamonds, geom = c("point", "smooth"))

Adding a smoother to a plot

  • If you want to turn the confidence interval off, use se=FALSE.

  • There are many different smoothers you can choose between by using the method argument:

    • method="loess", the default for small n, uses a smooth local regression to fit a polynomial surface determined by one or more numerical predictors.
    • method="lm" fits a linear model.

Adding a smoother to a plot

qplot(carat, price, data = dsmall, geom = c("point", "smooth"), method = "lm")

Boxplots and jittered points

  • When a set of data includes a categorical variable and one or more continuous variables, you will probably be interested to know how the values of the continuous variables vary with the levels of the categorical variable.

  • Boxplots and jittered points offer two ways to do this.

  • Each method has its strengths and weaknesses.

    • Boxplots summarize the bulk of the distribution with only five numbers;
    • Jittered plots show every point but can suffer from overplotting.

  • The overplotting seen in the plot of jittered values can be alleviated somewhat by using semi-transparent points using the alpha argument.

Boxplots and jittered points

qplot(color, price/carat, data = diamonds, geom = "boxplot")

Boxplots and jittered points

qplot(color, price/carat, data = diamonds, geom = "jitter")

Boxplots and jittered points

qplot(color, price/carat, data = diamonds, geom = "jitter", alpha = I(1/5))

Boxplots and jittered points

qplot(color, price/carat, data = diamonds, geom = "jitter", alpha = I(1/50))

Boxplots and jittered points

qplot(color, price/carat, data = diamonds, geom = "jitter", alpha = I(1/200))

Boxplots and jittered points

  • This technique cant show the positions of the quartiles as well as a boxplot can, but it may reveal other features of the distribution that a boxplot cannot.

  • For jittered points, qplot offers the same control over aesthetics: size, colour and shape.

  • For boxplots you can control the outline colour, the internal fill colour and the size of the lines.

Histogram and density plots

  • Histogram and density plots show the distribution of a single variable.

  • They provide more information about the distribution of a single group than boxplots do, but it is harder to compare many groups.

  • For the histogram, the binwidth argument controls the amount of smoothing by setting the bin size.

  • It is very important to experiment with the level of smoothing.

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "density")

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "histogram")

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "histogram", binwidth = 1, xlim = c(0, 
    3))

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "histogram", binwidth = 0.1, xlim = c(0, 
    3))

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "histogram", binwidth = 0.01, xlim = c(0, 
    3))

Histogram and density plots

  • To compare the distributions of different subgroups, just add an aesthetic mapping.

  • Mapping a categorical variable to an aesthetic will automatically split up the geom by that variable.

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "density", colour = color)

Histogram and density plots

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, geom = "histogram", fill = color)

Bar charts

  • The discrete analogue of histogram is the bar chart, geom="bar".

  • The bar geom counts the number of instances of each class automatically.

  • If you like to tabulate class members in some other way, you can use weight geom

Bar charts

qplot(color, data = diamonds, geom = "bar")

Bar charts

qplot(color, data = diamonds, geom = "bar", weight = carat)

Faceting

  • Faceting creates tables of graphics by splitting the data into subsets and displaying the same graph for each subset in an arrangement that facilitates comparison.

  • The default faceting method in qplot() creates plots arranged on a grid specified by a faceting formula which looks like row_var~col_var.

  • You can specify as many row and column variables as you like.

  • To facet on only one of columns or rows, use . as a place holder.

Faceting

qplot(carat, data = diamonds, facets = color ~ ., geom = "histogram", bindwidth = 0.1, 
    xlim = c(0, 3))

Faceting

qplot(carat, ..density.., data = diamonds, facets = color ~ ., geom = "histogram", 
    bindwidth = 0.1, xlim = c(0, 3))

  • The ..density.. syntax is new. The y-axis of the histogram is the probability instead of the original count from the dataset.

Other options

  • There are a few other qplot options to control the graphics appearance.

    • xlim, ylim: set limits for the x- and y-axes.
    • log: a character vector indicating which axes should be logged.
    • main: main title for the plot.
    • xlab, ylab: labels for the x- and y-axes.

  • The following examples show the options in action.

Other options

qplot(carat, price, data = dsmall, xlab = "Price($)", ylab = "Weight(carats)", 
    main = "Price-weight relationship")

Other options

qplot(carat, price/carat, data = dsmall, xlab = "Weight(carats)", ylab = expression(frac(price, 
    carat)), main = "Small diamonds", xlim = c(0.2, 1))

Other options

qplot(carat, price, data = dsmall, log = "xy")
